	<li class="comment odd alt depth-4" id="li-comment-328724">
		<div id="comment-328724">
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/8ee198bba323f520d2b9068973384629?s=48&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />
			<cite class="fn"><a href='http://TNTcombatives.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>TC</a></cite>

			<span class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
				|
				<a href="http://www.thesurvivalpodcast.com/examining-the-future-role-of-the-militia-in-modern-society/comment-page-1#comment-328724">
				May 9, 2013 at 11:12 am</a>
					|
													</span><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-body"><p>@Ryan</p>
<p>Your concept is valid, in CA it is called the State Military Reserve.  We also have very robust LEO reserve programs.  For example, I am a Sergeant with my county sheriffs office.  My Lt is both an Lt with the sheriffs office and a Major with the State Military Reserve.  Both organizations are primarily made up of volunteers.</p>
<p>Our LEO reserve division is 200+ sworn and 600+ volunteers. They all fall under a reserve command structure and have their own reserve peace officer association to handle Legal Defense and Injury/Disability.  Other reserve departments even include retirement benefits and retire LEO credentials for 50 state ccw. Our reserves are on S&amp;R, Harbor, Patrol, SWAT, HRW, K9, etc. and they must meet the same qualifications of the regulars.</p>
<p>Point is these organizations exist and are capable of helping their communities in all the ways you envision.  However, they are not the &#8220;militia&#8221;.</p>
</div>

